-- South African Stocks: Anglo American, BHP, Capital Shopping
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-08T16:20:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-08/south-african-stocks-drop-first-day-in-four-anglo-billiton-lead-decline.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  increased for a sixth day, gaining 5.51 points, or
0.02 percent, to 31,769.88 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), a diversified miner, slumped
for the first time in six days, losing 1.51 rand, or 0.5
percent, to 333.49 rand. Copper fell as much as 2 percent in
London.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), the world’s third-largest
gold producer, retreated for a second day, decreasing 2.41 rand,
or 0.7 percent, to 337.49 rand. Gold slid as much as 1.3 percent
to $1,384.38 an ounce.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL SJ), the world’s biggest mining
company, declined the most since Nov. 30, dropping 1.86 rand, or
0.7 percent, to 268.73 rand. Trade union Numsa said in a
statement that its members went on strike over pay at BHP’s
Bayside and Hillside aluminum smelters in South Africa.  Capital Shopping Centres Group Plc  (CSO SJ), the U.K.’s
largest shopping-mall owner, fell the most since May 14, losing
1.55 rand, or 3.5 percent, to 42.68 rand. The company said it
wouldn’t supply Simon Property Group Inc., the largest U.S. mall
owner, with information to help it evaluate a possible bid.
Simon said earlier it will end interest in buying Capital if the
U.K. company didn’t provide the information.  Grand Parade Investments Ltd.  (GPL SJ), the investment
company with interests in tourism and gaming, surged the most
since February, gaining 20 cents, or 7.1 percent, to 3 rand.
Grand Parade and  Sun International Ltd.  (SUI SJ), South Africa’s
biggest gaming company, said in a regulatory statement that they
are in talks about re-arranging their common interests in some
of Sun’s subsidiaries.  Sanlam Ltd.  (SLM SJ), the biggest South Africa-based
insurer, advanced for the first day in three, adding 23 cents,
or 0.9 percent, to 26.83 rand. The insurer said new business
volumes rose 4 percent in the 10 months ended October, and that
the value of new business was 7 percent higher, according to a
regulatory filing.  To contact the reporter on this story:
